{
  "local_port": 54644,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the procedure to check your PF balance?",
  "response": "You can check your Provident Fund (PF) balance through several methods, depending on the country you are in. Here\u2019s a general guideline for checking your PF balance, particularly for the Employees' Provident Fund (EPF) in India:\n\n### 1. **Using the EPFO Member Portal:**\n   - Visit the official EPFO website: [www.epfindia.gov.in](http://www.epfindia.gov.in).\n   - Click on \u201cEmployee\u201d under the \u201cFor Employees\u201d section.\n   - Click on \u201cMember Passbook\u201d and log in using your Universal Account Number (UAN) and password.\n   - You can view your balance and transaction details here.\n\n### 2. **Using the EPFO Mobile App:**\n   - Download the EPFO app from Google Play Store or Apple App Store.\n   - Log in using your UAN and password.\n   - You can check your balance under the \u201cEmployee Centric Services\u201d section.\n\n### 3. **SMS Facility:**\n   - You can send an SMS to know your balance. The format generally is:\n     ```\n     EPFOHO UAN <Last Four Digits of your Account Number>\n     ```\n   - Send this SMS to 7738299899. Make sure your UAN is registered with your mobile number.\n\n### 4. **Missed Call Service:**\n   - Give a missed call to 011-22901406 from the registered mobile number linked to your UAN. You will receive an SMS with your PF balance.\n\n### 5. **Employer's HR Department:**\n   - You can also contact your employer\u2019s HR or finance department for your PF balance and other related inquiries.\n\n### 6. **Using the UAN-based Online Services:**\n   - Log in to the EPFO website using your UAN and password.\n   - Navigate to the \"Manage\" section and check the \"Account Statement\" to view further details.\n\n### Key Points:\n- Make sure your UAN is activated and linked to your KYC details for smoother transactions.\n- If you don\u2019t have your UAN, check with your employer for assistance.\n  \nMake sure to follow the latest guidelines and services offered by the EPFO, as the procedure may evolve over time.",
